  "articleSummary": "The article argues that adding more engineers to a late project is counterproductive due to quadratic communication overhead (n(n-1)/2) and long onboarding times (3–6 months for senior hires), which drain existing team focus via mentorship and review. It cites Brooks' Law (1975) and modern research (e.g., *Accelerate*, *Team Topologies*) to show that coordination costs dominate, making smaller, autonomous teams (5–8 people, per Amazon's two-pizza rule) more effective. The tone is analytical with a frustrated edge, using recurring metaphors like the communication-path formula and \"mentorship tax\" to frame the argument. Intended audience: engineering managers and technical leads facing deadline pressure.",
